# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
"""
Parametric model railway curve and straight-track template generator for FreeCAD.

Version 10.2A8A7B14 adds automatic whole-workflow benchmarking across geometry, timbering, chair analysis, model support, 2D display, integration and optional export-chair preparation. It records wall time, process CPU time, current memory change and FreeCAD document-object change for every guided production stage, and adds a report/reset control without altering any accepted railway result. The routine 2D display now uses a low-detail Templot-guided S1/S1J plan symbol with a chamfered base, separate inner and outer jaw blocks and an optional key stroke, while retaining the exact source-dimensional footprint for validation. Version 10.2A8A7B13 adds a lightweight Templot-style 2D chair layout, an explicit bounded model-timber support stage and export-time-only 3D S1/S1J chair-body preparation. Required side extensions are derived from the actual rotated chair footprint, rounded upwards to 0.05 mm, kept separate from the prototype timber reference and rejected above the configured per-side limit. Version 10.2A8A7B12 adds transactional physical S1 and S1J chair-body generation and read-only fit validation against the fixed Templot5 556b C&L / EMGS / S4Soc Code 75 rev:A bullhead rail profile. It preserves unsupported and special chair positions as analytical records, leaves production readiness false while special chairs, keying and live fit remain outstanding, and changes no turnout, crossover, timber, host-integration or established exporter calculation. Version 10.2A8A7B11 removes redundant crossover metadata work by building final automatic-timbering and timber-analysis state once, serialising each persistent payload once, propagating the final state through one object pass, skipping property assignments whose values are already current, and updating the crossover catalogue once. It changes no railway geometry, sampling, tolerance, topology rule, timber decision, chair assignment or production record. Version 10.2A8A7B10 adds read-only live stage profiling around crossover timber analysis, shared long-timber solving, controlled conflict resolution, chair-position analysis, FreeCAD Part shape construction, diagnostic display updates and document recomputes. It changes no railway geometry, sampling, tolerance, acceptance rule or production record. Version 10.2A8A7B9 adds exact hierarchical path indexes, incremental analysis reuse and reduced FreeCAD display/recompute churn without changing any accepted railway result. Version 10.2A8A7B8 reduces chair-analysis and crossover-timbering run time without changing railway geometry, topology, timber placement rules, chair assignment rules or production exporters. It reuses identical in-memory timber analyses, removes duplicate final validation passes, batches timber-conflict diagnostics, builds only requested chair diagnostic layers, and uses a pre-indexed exact rail-projection path for chair-position discovery. Version 10.2A8A7B7 adds a shared guided turnout-and-crossover workflow panel which presents geometry, timbering, chair-position analysis, integration and finish actions as numbered human-readable steps. It calls the existing validated operations directly, hides specialist and maintenance controls by default, offers a safe Run next step action, and does not alter any turnout geometry, crossover solver, topology gate, timber calculation, chair calculation, host-integration calculation or exporter. Version 10.2A8A7B6 repairs the crossover topology regression by preserving each diverging branch end as a directed railway endpoint, using the outward Host A branch tangent and the reverse of the outward Host B branch tangent for connector traversal, rejecting tangent-continuous routes which leave towards a switch toe or intrude through either turnout, and extending operator diagnostics without altering turnout rail construction, timber-resolution limits, chair analysis, host integration or production exporters. Version 10.2A8A7B5 repaired curved-host crossover connector orientation by treating each turnout branch-end tangent as a bidirectional geometric line, selecting the direction which faces through the local connector chord, preserving host travel direction separately, prioritising the branch-end search region and expanding solver diagnostics. Version 10.2A8A7B4 adds a bounded arc-straight-arc local connector family, correct branch-end Host B toe seeding and faster staged solver tracing after host regeneration. Version 10.2A8A7B3 adds a tangent-exact cubic connector fallback and detailed read-only solver tracing when the exact biarc family cannot produce a local route after host regeneration. Version 10.2A8A7B2 repairs the remaining curved-host crossover rejection by replacing the over-strict endpoint-chord test with sampled local-route validation and an unequal-distance biarc family search. It retains loop rejection, exact end tangency, minimum-radius validation and transactional failure before any document geometry is created. Version 10.2A8A7B1 repairs crossover connector selection after host-curve regeneration by rejecting non-local looping biarcs and adaptively refining the neighbouring-host toe search before any document geometry is created. Version 10.2A8A7B assigns ordinary REA S1/S1J chairs and C-switch P, PLR block-slide and PLR block-heel supports, preserves key direction as an explicit configurable requirement where no policy is stored, and records read-only model-scale timber-support recommendations from confirmed chair footprints without generating chair solids or altering production geometry. Version 10.2A8A7A1 repairs live chair-analysis display height, binds inherited protected support to the applicable route and rail role, physically qualifies analytical footprint findings, and groups repeated advisory output without generating chair solids or changing production geometry. Version 10.2A8A7A adds a read-only stable chair-position and assignment framework, lightweight diagnostics, cache signatures and chair-aware production preflight without generating chair solids or altering production geometry. Version 10.2A8A6C2 repairs the selected-production export workflow, adds scrolling to both tabs of the unified turnout and crossover manager, and safely projects turnout engraving records to planar XY export copies without changing their FreeCAD display objects. Version 10.2A8A6C1 repairs managed-crossover production export by projecting crossover rail and construction-mark display geometry to safe planar XY engraving records and by validating only records which the selected export formats will actually write. Version 10.2A8A6C adds transactional crossover editing and reversible host-template integration of the final automatically resolved timber arrangement. Version 10.2A8A6B4A1 refines crossover timbering terminology and adds complete operator tooltips without changing resolver geometry. Version 10.2A8A6B4 adds a one-click hybrid automatic crossover timber resolver. It rebuilds the complete A8A6B2A2 shared-timber envelope in memory, applies the A8A6B3 interlacing and minimum controlled-shove solver only where long timbers cannot safely resolve the arrangement, validates the final effective timbering as one deterministic result, and retains unsafe positions explicitly rather than forcing geometry. Shared envelope timbers are assessed against every supported road normal instead of being reported as ordinary single-road sleepers. The B4 result remains a preview until A8A6C integrates it reversibly with the host templates; chair generation and fit validation remain staged for A8A7. Version 10.2A8A6A6 completes the reversible turnout/crossover lifecycle. A managed crossover can be converted transactionally back into a standalone turnout. Crossovers created from an existing turnout automatically restore that original Host A turnout and stable identity; independently created crossovers allow either constituent turnout to be retained. New turnout-to-crossover conversions also store the complete source-turnout configuration snapshot so future reversal restores all optional timber and datum outputs exactly.

Version 10.2A8A6A adds a managed natural REA C10 crossover geometry module and retains the A8A5 ability to integrate a validated REA C10 turnout into derived host-template production geometry and adds independent reference-copy extraction without modifying the original generated railway objects. It preserves the complete A8A4 source-driven turnout timbering and all established turnout rail geometry. It uses the published C-switch individual timber centres, evenly fits closure timbers within the available interlead, preserves the fixed REA crossing-chair spacings around the wing and vee rails, and provides correctly widening timber outlines, optional centre lines, timber identities, optional length labels and separate construction datums. The timber rectangles inherit the selected host alignment through the same proven station-normal mapping as the rail geometry, so their position and orientation remain coherent through straight, constant-radius and Euler-transition regions. Existing Version 10.2A8A1-A8A3 turnouts can be upgraded transactionally through Edit selected turnout and Apply turnout changes without altering their placement. The replacement geometry is fully built and validated in memory before one FreeCAD transaction updates the existing turnout identity and production records. It retains the complete A8A3 switch, closure, common-crossing, vee, wing-rail and check-rail geometry and the proven Version 10.2A7 configuration and named-preset system. Presets store reusable configuration snapshots only, can be transported inside configuration JSON, and are written to the user preset library only after an explicit save. It retains the complete
Version 10.2A2 production schedule and material report, together with the proven Version 10.0B3
curve, easement, straight, platform, formation-board, sectioning, assembly and production-export
geometry. This stage retains the established read-only production preflight system, adds a focused integrated-crossover readiness check, and retains repaired selected-item
production export, including persistent reconstruction of sloped platform-edge display wires as safe XY engraving records and deterministic filenames for the distinct track-centreline and platform-edge engraving outputs, and recognises intentional one-dimensional centreline and platform-edge engraving as valid linear output rather than noisy degenerate-span diagnostics, for FreeCAD object selections, highlighted production records, individual sections, complete tracks, platforms,
formation boards, routes and whole template sets. It filters the persistent production-record
catalogue, presents a complete file and overwrite preview, runs scope-aware preflight checks, then
writes every requested DXF, SVG, STL, STEP and CSV manifest into a hidden staging directory before
committing the complete file set. Any exporter, manifest or final-file failure rolls back the
operation and restores overwritten files. Legacy sets remain readable through the cautious Version
10.2A1 metadata scan. No railway geometry, numbering, sectioning, assembly, formation-board or
established exporter calculation is changed.

Connected straights continue to inherit the generated curve endpoints, headings, track
centres, template widths and output selections rather than recalculating or altering any
curve geometry. Independent straights retain their own datum, rotation, travel direction,
parallel side, spacing, width and thickness. Straight platforms remain deliberately
outside this revision so the established curved-platform manager is not destabilised.
A pre-transaction validation still requires every connected route to contain exactly one
straight alignment for every generated curve track.
The corrected Version 9.13 Platform Manager initialisation and every existing curve
output pathway remain intact. Accepted dialogue values remain remembered per document,
with a last-used fallback for new or renamed documents.

The formation board is deliberately simple and robust: one continuous swept outline
is calculated from the furthest occupied transverse limits of the selected track-template
strips and platforms along the route. Abrupt platform-end changes are broadened into
controlled longitudinal transitions, the ends are closed perpendicular to the route,
and the resulting single face is extruded downwards by the entered sheet thickness.
The base board uses no face-to-face Boolean fusions, holes or joints unless those
separate optional post-processing features are explicitly selected.

Each added track can use standard independent Euler geometry or the dedicated
platform-widening geometry. Every track has:

  * its own Euler entry and exit easements
  * its own concentric constant-radius section
  * independent entry, curve and exit centre spacing
  * automatic easement solving to match the requested straight spacings, or
    manual entry and exit easement lengths
  * no reverse curvature: curvature remains zero or follows the selected turn
    direction throughout the complete alignment
  * optional platform widening transitions with exact straight and curve spacing
  * an individual template width and output controls

The main curve defines the common circular centre and total turn angle. Added
tracks use the selected curve spacing to calculate their constant radius:

  Outside radius = main radius + curve spacing
  Inside radius  = main radius - curve spacing

Positive turn angles curve left; negative turn angles curve right. Run the macro
again to edit the stored settings.
"""

